00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:20.370
So why is this important?

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:22.110
Why do we care?

00:03:22.110 --> 00:03:25.350
Many of us, in fact, including
myself at one point in time,

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:27.930
believe that disability was
something that only affected

00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:31.920
a small set of the population.

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:35.240
Even in the strictest
sense, that set is massive.

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:39.850
It's a billion people, or 15%
of the world's population.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:42.670
But let's start to
think about disability

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:44.200
a little more holistically.

00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:48.310
So if we include people
who don't self-identify

00:03:48.310 --> 00:03:51.070
as having a disability,
this number-- one billion--

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:51.580
it doubles.

00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:52.810
It grows.

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:56.020
If we think of friends,
family, and loved

00:03:56.020 --> 00:03:58.510
ones of folks who
have disabilities,

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:01.000
well, then that
number grows again.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.830
And thinking of this
even more expansively,

00:04:05.830 --> 00:04:08.530
if we think about
disability to include people

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.620
with temporary conditions, like
a broken arm or a broken leg,

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:15.670
or situational ones like
driving and texting--

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:18.970
don't do it-- then
our circle expands

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:22.130
to include nearly
the entire planet.

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:25.330
So it's really
everyone's work to make

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:27.940
not just our products, but
the planet, more accessible.

00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.060
And when we do so, we're
affirming that accessibility

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:34.240
is a human right.

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.080
So apart from doing
the right thing,

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:39.670
I'm going to talk to you a
little bit today about why

00:04:39.670 --> 00:04:42.730
there are some very positive
karmic consequences when we

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:45.130
design for accessibility first.

00:04:45.130 --> 00:04:47.200
So much so, a term
is coined for it,

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:49.450
and that term is
the curb cut effect.

00:04:49.450 --> 00:04:52.270
So you see, back in the day,
there were no curb cuts,

00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:56.410
just as at one point in time,
there were no closed captions.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:05:00.700
So that meant that people who
use wheelchairs effectively

00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:05.420
encountered a wall every
time they came to a curb.

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:09.970
So in 1945, there was a guy
in Kalamazoo, Michigan, named

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:12.250
Jeff Fisher, who is disabled.

00:05:12.250 --> 00:05:14.950
And he advocated and
fought for the installation

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:19.780
of the country's first curb cut,
and they caught on globally.

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:23.470
Sidewalks, and more
importantly, cities,

00:05:23.470 --> 00:05:29.210
became independently navigable
for the very first time.

00:05:29.210 --> 00:05:31.830
And this had
positive consequences

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:32.880
literally for everyone.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:35.340
For parents, with
kids in strollers,

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.220
for people toting
luggage, for workers

00:05:38.220 --> 00:05:40.710
with dollies or hand trucks.

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:45.150
And now today, we can't even
imagine a world without them,

00:05:45.150 --> 00:05:48.120
because we're much safer and
it's much easier to get along--

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:49.200
to get around.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:52.990
And this is what was
dubbed the curb cut effect.

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:56.700
Another realization of the curb
cut effect is closed captions.

00:05:56.700 --> 00:05:58.860
Personally, I love captions.

00:05:58.860 --> 00:06:02.030
They're great for the World
Series or the World Cup

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.800
at a loud bar.

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:06.120
They let me listen in
silence when I'm on the train

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:09.480
or at the library, or I don't
want to bother my co-workers.

00:06:09.480 --> 00:06:12.410
As awesome as they
are for me, they're

00:06:12.410 --> 00:06:17.420
game-changing for the 466
million people on the planet

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:19.140
who have hearing loss.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:22.830
