00:11:37.070 --> 00:11:40.960
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:41.650
Hi, everyone.

00:11:41.650 --> 00:11:45.000
My name is Melissa Barnhart,
and I'm a researcher on Android.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.400
And today, I'd like to talk to
you about the user experience.

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:53.630
So when you think about
the user experience,

00:11:53.630 --> 00:11:56.640
I'd like you to
think about empathy.

00:11:56.640 --> 00:11:59.390
Empathy is at the
heart of design.

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:01.310
Without the
understanding of what

00:12:01.310 --> 00:12:04.100
others see, feel,
and experience,

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:06.560
design is a pointless task.

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:09.150
And to be empathetic
technologists,

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:11.510
we have to set aside
our own assumptions

00:12:11.510 --> 00:12:13.590
and consider other perspectives.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:18.800
Now, a great way
to build empathy

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:20.630
is through user research.

00:12:20.630 --> 00:12:23.990
User research focuses on
understanding behaviors

00:12:23.990 --> 00:12:26.660
and needs through a
variety of methodologies

00:12:26.660 --> 00:12:31.430
like interviews, observations,
or survey, just to name a few.

00:12:31.430 --> 00:12:33.650
Like a compass,
user research can

00:12:33.650 --> 00:12:36.740
help point you and your
product in the right direction.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:38.930
And you can utilize
user research

00:12:38.930 --> 00:12:42.950
at any stage in your design
and development process.

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:45.260
Before you begin
building, user research

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:49.230
can uncover unmet needs
and inspire designs

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:51.440
that actually meet those needs.

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:53.780
The number one reason
for startup failure

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.810
is lack of market
need for a product,

00:12:56.810 --> 00:13:00.080
but you can minimize this
risk by conducting research

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:02.660
before development even begins.

00:13:02.660 --> 00:13:04.940
And when development
is underway,

00:13:04.940 --> 00:13:07.760
user research can help you
evaluate different design

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:11.840
solutions and ensure that your
user experience stays on track.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:14.120
And then when your product
is out in the market,

00:13:14.120 --> 00:13:15.920
you can use research
to help measure

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:19.205
the impact of your designs
and also to show the ROI.

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:25.060
So today, I'd like to share
an example of how we've

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:29.260
used user research to improve
Live Transcribe, a new Android

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:31.930
application that provides
real-time transcription

00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:34.090
for the deaf and
hard of hearing.

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:36.070
A team of research
scientists at Google

00:13:36.070 --> 00:13:40.150
identified a new opportunity
for automatic speech recognition

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:45.100
and built the first prototype
for Live Transcribe.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:49.430
So we have the technology, but
what about the user experience?

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.780
We had a lot of questions
about Live Transcribe

00:13:54.780 --> 00:13:57.870
that we hoped to address through
research with the deaf and hard

00:13:57.870 --> 00:13:59.620
of hearing participants.

00:13:59.620 --> 00:14:01.920
For example, what are
their first impressions

00:14:01.920 --> 00:14:03.540
of Live Transcribe?

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:05.670
Also, how would they
expect scrolling

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:09.180
to work in both landscape
and portrait orientations?

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:11.460
Should it scroll
from top to bottom,

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:13.920
should it kind of fade
away, or should it

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:15.930
resemble a physical book?

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:20.250
But our most pressing question
was about the visual design.

00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:24.390
What font style, type form,
text size, text color,

00:14:24.390 --> 00:14:27.150
and background color
should we default to?

00:14:27.150 --> 00:14:29.790
We assumed that users
would want to see

00:14:29.790 --> 00:14:33.420
differently-colored
confidence levels to indicate

00:14:33.420 --> 00:14:35.500
the accuracy of
the transcription,

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:37.560
but we didn't know for sure.

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:40.290
And good research starts
with good research questions

00:14:40.290 --> 00:14:41.160
like these ones.

00:14:43.850 --> 00:14:45.730
So to answer our
research questions,

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:47.740
we took a mixed
methods approach.

00:14:47.740 --> 00:14:51.040
We started with a usability
study in a Google lab

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:53.350
to evaluate our
minimum viable product

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:56.680
with people who had moderate
to profound hearing loss.

00:14:56.680 --> 00:14:58.750
But we also wanted to
know how people would

00:14:58.750 --> 00:15:01.570
use Live Transcribe over time.

00:15:01.570 --> 00:15:04.750
How would it work in different
environments like in the home

00:15:04.750 --> 00:15:07.990
or in the classroom,
and would people's needs

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:10.390
change with continued use?

00:15:10.390 --> 00:15:13.150
So to answer these
questions, we partnered

00:15:13.150 --> 00:15:16.750
with Gallaudet University,
the world's premier university

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:18.520
for the deaf and
hard of hearing.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:20.470
And that collaboration
allowed us

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:24.070
to collect longitudinal feedback
from faculty and students

00:15:24.070 --> 00:15:27.550
who used Live Transcribe
in everyday life.

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:30.880
And after iterating on our
designs based on their feedback

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:33.430
and adding new
functionality, we conducted

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:36.310
a second lab-based
usability study again

00:15:36.310 --> 00:15:38.770
with participants who had
moderate to profound hearing

00:15:38.770 --> 00:15:41.680
loss.

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:44.320
OK, so let's dig into those
lab studies a little bit.

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:46.480
Our protocols started
with questions

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:50.470
like tell me about a time when
you use real time captioning?

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:52.300
What did you like
about the experience

00:15:52.300 --> 00:15:54.820
and what did you dislike
about the experience?

00:15:54.820 --> 00:15:56.890
So background
questions helped us

00:15:56.890 --> 00:16:01.150
understand previous experiences
as well as current needs.

00:16:01.150 --> 00:16:03.880
Then we enabled the
prototype, and we handed it

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:05.230
to the participant.

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:08.410
And for the next 60 minutes,
we initiated conversation

00:16:08.410 --> 00:16:11.920
about a variety of topics
and generally observed

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:14.780
how the participants
interacted with the phone.

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:17.200
We also evaluated
different text flows

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:20.300
and probed for feedback
on the visual design.

00:16:20.300 --> 00:16:24.250
So in our prototype,
white italicized text

00:16:24.250 --> 00:16:29.050
signified unfinalized text
whereas yellow normal text

00:16:29.050 --> 00:16:31.510
represented finalized text.

00:16:31.510 --> 00:16:35.350
Did these participants
understand that color and type

00:16:35.350 --> 00:16:38.530
form indicated confidence
in the transcription,

00:16:38.530 --> 00:16:40.405
and was that information
even valuable?

00:16:43.350 --> 00:16:45.300
So it was in this
research that we

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:48.720
learned that changing the
type form and text color

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:52.470
actually distracted participants
from the conversation.

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:55.380
Additionally, our
participants self-reported

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:58.440
that italics made reading
more difficult for them,

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:00.330
and these insights
were reinforced

00:17:00.330 --> 00:17:02.700
by previous research
in this space which

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:05.609
says that a transcript is
easiest to read when it's not

00:17:05.609 --> 00:17:08.099
layered with these
extra signals.

00:17:08.099 --> 00:17:11.310
We also learned that our
original scrolling text

00:17:11.310 --> 00:17:14.369
flow felt natural, unlike
the other flows that we

00:17:14.369 --> 00:17:15.450
showed participants.

00:17:15.450 --> 00:17:17.814
It didn't force them
to shift their eyes

00:17:17.814 --> 00:17:19.064
to another part of the screen.

00:17:22.319 --> 00:17:24.950
So because of these
insights, we removed

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:27.200
those colorful
confidence levels.

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:30.950
We used a normal type forum
instead of an italic type form.

00:17:30.950 --> 00:17:33.890
And we proceeded with
the scrolling text flow.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:35.280
And this is just the beginning.

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:36.830
We'll continue to
make improvements

00:17:36.830 --> 00:17:39.120
as we conduct further research.

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:42.360
But what I really hope to show
today is the power of empathy.

00:17:42.360 --> 00:17:44.960
So by putting aside
our own assumptions

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:47.540
about the visual design
and conducting research

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:51.110
with our target audience, we
changed the product design

00:17:51.110 --> 00:17:54.940
to be more legible and
ultimately accessible.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:58.924
And next up is Lauren here to
talk to us about dexterity.

00:17:58.924 --> 00:17:59.557
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:59.557 --> 00:18:00.890
LAUREN WINSTON: Thanks, Melissa.

00:18:00.890 --> 00:18:01.445
Hi, everyone.

00:18:01.445 --> 00:18:03.320
My name's Lauren, and
I'm a software engineer

00:18:03.320 --> 00:18:05.250
on central accessibility.

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:07.430
Now let's talk a little
bit about dexterity,

00:18:07.430 --> 00:18:10.490
the challenges users with
dexterity impairment face,

00:18:10.490 --> 00:18:14.430
and the services on Android
to help with these challenges.

00:18:14.430 --> 00:18:17.370
According to the US census,
more than 50 million people,

00:18:17.370 --> 00:18:19.410
or more than 19% of
the US population,

00:18:19.410 --> 00:18:21.690
has some form of
mobility impairment.

00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:24.887
Moreso in the US, more than
two million of these people

00:18:24.887 --> 00:18:26.970
have an impairment that
impacts how understandable

00:18:26.970 --> 00:18:28.410
their speech is.

00:18:28.410 --> 00:18:31.080
Over 50 million people
have limited dexterity

00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:33.570
in their hands, and
nearly 20 million people

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:36.180
have difficulty
lifting and grasping.

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:41.250
The majority of this population
is over 65 years old.

00:18:41.250 --> 00:18:43.200
Those with severe
dexterity challenges

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:46.650
include those with conditions
such as ALS, cerebral palsy,

00:18:46.650 --> 00:18:49.410
Parkinson's, or
spinal cord injuries.

00:18:49.410 --> 00:18:51.930
Some conditions result
in users experiencing

00:18:51.930 --> 00:18:55.380
involuntary movements such
as spasms and tremors.

00:18:55.380 --> 00:18:57.450
They may also have
difficulties with speech

00:18:57.450 --> 00:18:59.700
and having their
speech understood.

00:18:59.700 --> 00:19:02.940
Many conditions impacting
dexterity are progressive.

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:07.200
As loss of dexterity happens,
fine motor skills may regress.

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:09.480
People might have difficulty
with picking things up

00:19:09.480 --> 00:19:11.520
or maintaining a hold on items.

00:19:11.520 --> 00:19:13.050
Grasping or interacting
with a phone

00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:14.880
can be particularly
challenging for people

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:17.160
within this population.

00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:18.780
There are varying
levels of severity

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:22.050
of dexterity impairments, and we
offer various apps and services

00:19:22.050 --> 00:19:24.420
on Android that can be
used to help users based

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:25.755
on their own individual needs.

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:31.360
We introduced Accessibility
Menu last year

00:19:31.360 --> 00:19:33.970
designed to make common
interactions easier for people

00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:36.090
with dexterity challenges.

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:39.760
Accessibility Menu simplifies
common actions such as power

00:19:39.760 --> 00:19:42.100
off, locking the
screen, and accessing

00:19:42.100 --> 00:19:44.500
notifications in recent apps.

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:46.600
When enabled, it can
be opened via a button

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:48.130
at the bottom of
the screen, which

00:19:48.130 --> 00:19:50.080
helps those with limited reach.

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:52.960
Now we're adding new controls
for volume and brightness

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:55.690
so the user can continuously
adjust volume and brightness

00:19:55.690 --> 00:19:57.490
without leaving the menu.

00:19:57.490 --> 00:20:00.700
We've also added an option
for large buttons and settings

00:20:00.700 --> 00:20:04.330
to make the menu buttons larger.

00:20:04.330 --> 00:20:06.730
So those that may have
more limited hand dexterity

00:20:06.730 --> 00:20:10.240
can use Voice Access to
control their phone via voice.

00:20:10.240 --> 00:20:13.030
Voice Access uses voice
commands to perform gestures

00:20:13.030 --> 00:20:15.010
on elements on the
screen without needing

00:20:15.010 --> 00:20:16.930
to physically touch the phone.

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:18.580
Voice Access was
recently launched

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:20.380
in September of last year.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:27.020
You can download it now
at g.co/voiceaccess.

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:29.180
Voice Access places
an overlay of numbers

00:20:29.180 --> 00:20:31.400
over the actionable
elements on a screen.

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.000
Simply speak to your phone
with actions such as "click 7"

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.760
or "go back" to interact
with your phone.

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:39.290
When Voice Access
is enabled, you

00:20:39.290 --> 00:20:41.300
can continue using your
usual Google Assistant

00:20:41.300 --> 00:20:45.130
commands, such as setting a
timer or checking the weather.

00:20:45.130 --> 00:20:47.990
A feedback bar is always present
at the top of the screen that

00:20:47.990 --> 00:20:49.820
captures your spoken phrases.

00:20:49.820 --> 00:20:52.220
You can specifically
refer to elements

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:53.990
by their number
such as "top seven"

00:20:53.990 --> 00:20:55.920
or you can refer to the
name of the elements.

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:57.680
So if you wanted to
open an app, like you

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:02.003
wanted to open Google Keep,
you could say "open Keep."

00:21:02.003 --> 00:21:04.170
We're also happy to announce
that we brought support

00:21:04.170 --> 00:21:06.555
to French, Italian,
German, and Spanish.

00:21:09.320 --> 00:21:11.150
So Voice Access
is great for those

00:21:11.150 --> 00:21:14.067
with limited hand dexterity
and understandable speech.

00:21:14.067 --> 00:21:15.650
But there's many out
there who may not

00:21:15.650 --> 00:21:17.360
be able to speak clearly.

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:20.630
For those Android users
we have Switch Access.

00:21:20.630 --> 00:21:23.360
Switch Access allows users
with limited hand dexterity

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:25.850
and limited speech to navigate
through their phone using

00:21:25.850 --> 00:21:27.590
external buttons or switches.

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:30.270
I'll show you what a typical
switch might look like.

00:21:30.270 --> 00:21:32.060
So a typical switch
could look something

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:34.430
like this with
two large buttons,

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:37.640
and a user can interact with
the switch with their hands,

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:40.250
or if they have more control
on other parts of their body,

00:21:40.250 --> 00:21:42.000
they may use another
part of their bodies,

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.290
such as their feet.

00:21:44.290 --> 00:21:47.030
In a common two-switch
case, one switch

00:21:47.030 --> 00:21:49.430
can be likened to a Tab
that moves the highlight

00:21:49.430 --> 00:21:52.130
on the screen when pressed,
while a second switch can

00:21:52.130 --> 00:21:54.710
be thought of as an Enter that
selects the highlighted item

00:21:54.710 --> 00:21:55.850
when pressed.

00:21:55.850 --> 00:21:58.700
Switches can be configured
to meet user needs,

00:21:58.700 --> 00:22:02.330
and switch access can be used
with as little as one switch.

00:22:02.330 --> 00:22:05.000
Most input devices work with
Switch Access, including

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:09.010
just a regular USB keyboard.

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:12.500
So text editing is commonly a
pain point for switch users.

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:15.340
So we recently added
text-editing menus.

00:22:15.340 --> 00:22:18.520
These menus add shortcuts for
previously time-consuming text

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:21.550
editing tasks, such as
highlighting and deleting

00:22:21.550 --> 00:22:26.170
text, undoing or redoing
actions, copy, cut, and paste.

00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:28.960
This allows text editing to
be done much more quickly,

00:22:28.960 --> 00:22:31.450
and with the use of as
little as one switch.

00:22:31.450 --> 00:22:32.940
I'll show a quick demo of this.

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:40.150
OK, so in this demo,
I'm using switches

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:41.848
configured to the volume keys.

00:22:41.848 --> 00:22:43.390
Assigning switches
to the volume keys

00:22:43.390 --> 00:22:45.040
is a very easy
way for developers

00:22:45.040 --> 00:22:47.170
to test out Switch
Access on their own apps

00:22:47.170 --> 00:22:49.600
without needing to have
an external switch.

00:22:49.600 --> 00:22:51.310
So using the volume
keys, I'm going

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:53.560
to go through the
elements on the screen

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:55.870
until I get to the text
field I wish to edit.

00:22:55.870 --> 00:22:59.290
I can select the text field,
and it brings up our text menu.

00:22:59.290 --> 00:23:00.790
So I want to move a word around.

00:23:00.790 --> 00:23:04.188
So I will go to highlight and
then choose the granularity

00:23:04.188 --> 00:23:05.230
that I wish to highlight.

00:23:05.230 --> 00:23:08.050
So I'll choose Highlight
Previous Word, which highlights

00:23:08.050 --> 00:23:10.120
this word "peaches" here.

00:23:10.120 --> 00:23:14.300
Then I can cut the
word with the menu.

00:23:14.300 --> 00:23:17.630
And then now I want to paste
the words somewhere else.

00:23:17.630 --> 00:23:21.350
So to do this, I first
need to move the cursor.

00:23:21.350 --> 00:23:25.030
So I can go to
Previous, and then I'll

00:23:25.030 --> 00:23:28.900
do previous line to move to the
beginning of this text field,

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:34.820
and then I can place
the word there.

00:23:34.820 --> 00:23:37.240
But what if I made a mistake?

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:40.990
We have undo and redo
actions added to these menus.

00:23:40.990 --> 00:23:44.300
Text-editing mistakes can be
very costly for switch users,

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.560
so these actions allow our
users to go more quickly

00:23:47.560 --> 00:23:49.072
back to text editing.

00:23:49.072 --> 00:23:50.530
And now I'll go
back to the slides.

00:23:55.810 --> 00:23:58.450
OK, so switching gears,
let's talk a little bit

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:01.730
about what's new for vision.

00:24:01.730 --> 00:24:03.320
To start with,
here's a little bit

00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:05.600
of background on
this population.

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:07.850
According to the World
Health Organization,

00:24:07.850 --> 00:24:11.120
it's estimated that 253
million people globally

00:24:11.120 --> 00:24:13.910
live with moderate to
severe visual impairment,

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:16.510
and people over 50
are most at risk.

00:24:16.510 --> 00:24:18.977
36 million of these
people are blind.

00:24:18.977 --> 00:24:20.810
We're here to help
people within vision loss

00:24:20.810 --> 00:24:23.820
be able to access and enjoy
not just their phones,

00:24:23.820 --> 00:24:26.880
but the world around them.

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:28.660
Lookout is an Android
app that helps

00:24:28.660 --> 00:24:30.430
make the real world
accessible for people

00:24:30.430 --> 00:24:33.520
who are blind or low vision
by helping them complete tasks

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:35.590
and routines more independently.

00:24:35.590 --> 00:24:38.440
We launched Lookout
in March of this year.

00:24:38.440 --> 00:24:40.360
Now I'll show a quick
video that speaks

00:24:40.360 --> 00:24:42.370
a little more to
what Lookout does

00:24:42.370 --> 00:24:45.568
and how it's used by our users.

